Understanding user needs is fundamental in software development to ensure the final product meets both user expectations and business goals. This process involves gathering requirements through surveys, interviews, user observations, and market analysis (Sommerville, 2016). In the SNHUTravel project, key functionalities such as travel booking, personalized recommendations, payment processing, and user account management were identified. These requirements were then translated into functional specifications, wireframes, and prototypes to guide development (Pressman & Maxim, 2020). Techniques like use case modeling and UML diagrams helped structure workflows and predict system interactions. Additionally, user stories played a crucial role in Agile development, as they broke down complex requirements into actionable tasks, clarified user expectations, and prioritized high-value features (Cohn, 2004).
A structured yet flexible approach was used for development, starting with requirement analysis and followed by planning, design, coding, testing, and deployment. Agile methodologies, including Scrum for iterative progress and Kanban for task visualization, facilitated adaptability and collaboration (Schwaber & Sutherland, 2020). Test-Driven Development (TDD) improved software quality by requiring tests before implementation (Beck, 2003), while Continuous Integration/Deployment (CI/CD) streamlined development by automating build and testing processes (Fowler & Foemmel, 2006). To ensure effective teamwork, developers must communicate clearly, collaborate efficiently, write maintainable code, and stay updated with industry trends (Brooks, 1995). By applying these methodologies, software solutions can be scalable, user-centered, and aligned with evolving business and user needs.

References
Beck, K. (2003). Test-driven development: By example. Addison-Wesley.
Brooks, F. P. (1995). The Mythical Man-Month: Essays on Software Engineering. Addison-Wesley.
Cohn, M. (2004). User Stories Applied: For Agile Software Development. Addison-Wesley.
Fowler, M., & Foemmel, M. (2006). Continuous Integration. ThoughtWorks.
Pressman, R. S., & Maxim, B. R. (2020). Software engineering: A practitioner’s approach (9th ed.). McGraw-Hill.
Schwaber, K., & Sutherland, J. (2020). The Scrum Guide. Scrum Alliance.
Sommerville, I. (2016). Software engineering (10th ed.). Pearson.
